# Building and writing the final page

## Reader promise

- Finish the walkthrough by combining compiler artefacts, runtime code, builder
  policy and output ownership.
- End with the exact fragment `<p>Hello, Priya!</p>`.

## Entry state

- Entry assembly, target-labelled functions, JavaScript and Wasm outputs,
  runtime helpers, external glue and tracked assets.
- Running checkpoint: all compiler and backend facts are explicit records.

## Opening problem

- The builder must turn many selected artefacts into one working document and
  a safe output set.
- It must not rediscover source structure or let each backend write files.

## Section sequence

### Assembly inputs

- List entry assembly, folded fragments, runtime slots, selected functions,
  Wasm variants, helpers, glue, assets and entry config.

### Document shell and fragments

- Plan route and document metadata.
- Insert compile-time fragments at recorded indexes.
- Invoke `start` once and hydrate runtime fragments in source order.

### Reactive and external work

- Mark reactive mount work as a target-specific extension.
- Explain demand-driven external JavaScript assets and import maps.

### Tracked assets and records

- Connect path usages and builder-owned asset decisions.
- Introduce output records, output-root validation and manifests.

### Writing and ownership

- Explain skip-unchanged writes, stale cleanup and builder ownership.
- State that one builder cannot delete another builder's files.

### Final checkpoint

- Show the conceptual output tree.
- Return to `<p>Hello, Priya!</p>` and stop the primary series here.

## What can fail here

- Invalid route or output path, missing asset, duplicate output, failed target
  record or stale-file ownership conflict.
- Keep backend generation failures in the backend article.

## Why Beanstalk does it this way

- Alternative: let each backend write files or let builders rescan source.
- Choice: central output records, validation, manifests and stale cleanup.
- Benefit: output ownership stays auditable and repeatable.
- Cost: builders must declare every produced file and ownership transition.

## Roadmap and current status

- Accepted design: build-system-owned output writing and manifests.
- Current implementation: link current HTML, asset and backend progress rows.
- Queued work: `html_project_backend_wasm_final_implementation_plan.md` and
  `entry-config-blocks-runtime-title-plan.md`.
- Deferred or outside scope: backend-owned output directories and hidden
  stale-file deletion.

